// Aha! Roadmaps for Beginners - Question Bank (GIFT)
// Import into Moodle Question bank, then build a quiz drawing random questions.

::RM01_RoadmapPurpose::
What is the primary purpose of a product roadmap?
{
=To communicate direction and priorities over time to align stakeholders
~To list every task engineers will complete this sprint
~To replace project plans and detailed schedules
~To document every historical release
}

::RM02_RoadmapVsPlan::
A roadmap is best described as:
{
=High-level communication of intent and priorities
~A day-by-day execution schedule
~A list of tickets with assignees
~A retrospective report of what shipped
}

::RM03_AudienceFirst::
Which practice most improves roadmap usefulness?
{
=Tailor the view and level of detail to the audience
~Show every internal field to be transparent
~Use only technical language for accuracy
~Avoid updating it to prevent confusion
}

::RM04_NowNextLater::
When is a “Now / Next / Later” roadmap especially helpful?
{
=When dates are uncertain but priorities are clear
~When you must provide exact delivery dates
~When you have no strategic goals
~When you want to document completed work
}

::RM05_MinimalStructure::
A common minimal structure to build a roadmap is:
{
=Goals/initiatives → releases → features
~Epics → sprints → bugs only
~Sales leads → deals → invoices
~Ideas only (no releases or features)
}

::RM06_ReleaseMeaning::
In a typical Aha! setup, a release usually represents:
{
=A planned delivery window that groups features
~A single user story
~A weekly timesheet
~A support ticket queue
}

::RM07_FeatureMeaning::
A feature is best understood as:
{
=A piece of work that delivers value and can be scheduled in a release
~A company mission statement
~A completed retrospective note
~An internal HR policy
}

::RM08_SavedViewsPurpose::
Why create a saved view in Aha! Roadmaps?
{
=To reuse the same filtered/customized roadmap later and share it consistently
~To permanently delete old roadmap drafts
~To automatically approve all roadmap changes
~To convert all features into ideas
}

::RM09_FirstDeclutterStep::
If a roadmap is too busy, the first best step is usually to:
{
=Apply filters and hide fields that are not relevant to the audience
~Add more items so the pattern is clearer
~Switch everything to daily granularity
~Export to PDF immediately
}

::RM10_ExternalTiming::
Which statement is safest when sharing roadmap timing externally?
{
=Share ranges/themes and clarify that dates may change as priorities evolve
~Share exact dates and guarantee delivery
~Share internal staffing constraints in full
~Avoid sharing any roadmap information at all
}

::RM11_TrustworthyRoadmaps::
What is a good habit to keep roadmaps trustworthy?
{
=Update the roadmap when priorities or delivery windows change
~Only update once per year
~Never remove items once published
~Use a separate spreadsheet for each audience
}

::RM12_SharingApproach::
Which is a sensible approach to sharing roadmaps?
{
=Use saved views and appropriate permissions to control what each audience sees
~Email screenshots and ask people not to forward them
~Share the admin account so everyone can access everything
~Export once and never revisit
}
